Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Dart source is byte-addressable UTF-8 (Dart's specification mandates UTF-8
encoding for source files). The lexer's cursor is a byte position rather
than a code-point index because Dart identifiers and keywords are ASCII
only - non-ASCII sequences appear only in string literals where the lexer
treats them opaquely. line/column track 1-based positions for error
reporting; length caches the source size to avoid recomputation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
40-byte record (5 x i64) at offsets 0..32: source (StringCore handle),
position (byte index, 0-based), line (1-based), column (1-based), length
(cached string length). Allocated from the arena rather than the heap
because lexer lifetime is bounded by the parse driver call.
@End Implementation

Type called "DartLexer":
    source as Integer
    position as Integer
    line as Integer
    column as Integer
    length as Integer
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Allocates a 40-byte lexer state record from the arena: source pointer
(offset 0), cursor index (offset 8) starting at 0, current line (offset
16) at 1, current column (offset 24) at 1, and source length (offset 32)
precomputed once via string_length so scanning loops don't re-walk the
buffer.
@End Reasoning

Process called "create_dart_lexer" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create Dart lexer from source code

    @Reasoning:
    Initialize lexer state with source code string and position tracking.
    Dart uses Unicode, so we track line/column for proper error reporting.
    @End Reasoning

    Let lexer be proc allocate from Arena with 40
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with lexer, 0, source
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with lexer, 16, 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with lexer, 24, 1
    Let len be proc string_length from StringCore with source
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with lexer, 32, len

    Return lexer
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A 32-byte token record holding type tag (0), lexeme string handle (8),
source line (16), and source column (24). Arena allocation matches the
parser's lifetime — tokens are owned by the parse run that produced
them and are released as a single batch when the arena is reset.
@End Reasoning

Process called "create_token" takes token_type as Integer, lexeme as Integer, line as Integer, column as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create token with type and metadata

    Let token be proc allocate from Arena with 32
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with token, 0, token_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with token, 8, lexeme
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with token, 16, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with token, 24, column

    Return token
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexeme Extraction
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Extracts the half-open byte range [start_pos, end_pos) of the source
buffer into a freshly allocated NUL-terminated string. The lexer slices
lexemes out of the single source buffer this way so tokens own stable
string handles independent of cursor movement. Defensive clamp: a
negative length (caller passed reversed bounds) produces the empty
string rather than corrupting memory.
@End Reasoning
Process called "dart_substring" takes source as Integer, start_pos as Integer, end_pos as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Copy source bytes [start_pos, end_pos) into a new NUL-terminated string

    Let len be end_pos minus start_pos
    If len is less than 0:
        Set len to 0
    End If

    Let buffer be proc allocate from Arena with len plus 1
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than len:
        Let ch be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with source, start_pos plus i
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, i, ch
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, len, 0
    Return buffer
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Classification
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Digit classification is needed for numeric-literal scanning and for the
alnum predicate used in identifier tail-character matching. Tests the
ASCII byte range 48..57 ('0'..'9') exclusively because Dart numeric
literals are ASCII per spec.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Single range comparison: 48 <= ch <= 57 returns 1, otherwise 0. Two nested
If's avoid a compound boolean expression. Constant-time.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_digit" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is digit (0-9)

    If ch is greater than or equal to 48:
        If ch is less than or equal to 57:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifier-start classifier: Dart identifiers begin with letter or
underscore (U+005F). Non-ASCII identifier letters (per Unicode) are not
supported in this lexer because Dart's idiomatic style uses ASCII names;
ASCII coverage is sufficient for the C-family-style identifier grammar.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 for '_' (95), 'A'..'Z' (65..90), and 'a'..'z' (97..122). Three
nested-If range checks; constant time.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_alpha" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphabetic (a-z, A-Z, _)

    If ch is equal to 95:
        Return 1
    End If

    If ch is greater than or equal to 65:
        If ch is less than or equal to 90:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If ch is greater than or equal to 97:
        If ch is less than or equal to 122:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifier-tail classifier: Dart identifier characters after the first
include digits in addition to letters/underscore. Reuses is_digit and
is_alpha for clarity.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 if is_digit returns 1, otherwise returns the is_alpha result
directly. Constant time.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_alnum" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphanumeric

    Let digit_check be proc is_digit with ch
    If digit_check is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let alpha_check be proc is_alpha with ch
    Return alpha_check
End Process

@Reasoning:
Hexadecimal classifier supports 0x... literal scanning. Accepts 0..9,
A..F, and a..f. Distinct from is_alnum because hex digits don't include
G..Z.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 if is_digit returns 1; otherwise tests 'A'..'F' (65..70) and
'a'..'f' (97..102) via nested If range checks.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_hex_digit" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is hexadecimal digit

    Let digit_check be proc is_digit with ch
    If digit_check is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    If ch is greater than or equal to 65:
        If ch is less than or equal to 70:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If ch is greater than or equal to 97:
        If ch is less than or equal to 102:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Whitespace classifier covers the four whitespace bytes used by Dart in
practice: space (0x20), tab (0x09), LF (0x0A), CR (0x0D). Vertical-tab
and form-feed are not used in Dart source.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Four equality checks; returns 1 on match, 0 otherwise. Constant time.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_whitespace" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is whitespace

    If ch is equal to 32:
        Return 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 9:
        Return 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 10:
        Return 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 13:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Utility Functions
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Read-only cursor accessor. Returns 0 (EOF sentinel) when at or past
length; this matches how character scanners check for end-of-input
without a separate eof flag.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads source/position/length from offsets 0/8/32. If position >= length
returns 0. Otherwise calls string_char_at from StringCore with the source
and position and returns the byte.
@End Implementation

Process called "current_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get current character without advancing

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 0
    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
    Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 32

    If position is greater than or equal to length:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, position
    Return ch
End Process

@Reasoning:
Multi-byte lookahead for disambiguating multi-character operators ("==",
"!=", "<<", ">>=", etc.) and for distinguishing identifiers from
contextual keywords without committing the cursor.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads source/position/length. Computes peek_pos = position + offset. If
peek_pos >= length returns 0 (EOF). Otherwise returns the byte at
peek_pos. Negative offsets are not validated; callers must pass
non-negative values.
@End Implementation

Process called "peek_char" takes lexer as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek ahead offset characters

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 0
    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
    Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 32
    Let peek_pos be position plus offset

    If peek_pos is greater than or equal to length:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, peek_pos
    Return ch
End Process

@Reasoning:
Cursor-advancing read. Updates line/column counters so error messages
quote correct source locations. Newline (0x0A) resets column to 1 and
bumps line; any other byte bumps column by 1. CR is handled implicitly
(its column bump still happens; the LF that follows in CRLF then resets).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls current_char to load the byte at the cursor. Bumps position by 1.
If the byte is 10 (LF), increments line and resets column to 1; otherwise
increments column. Returns the byte that was at the original cursor.
@End Implementation

Process called "advance_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Advance position and return current character

    Let ch be proc current_char with lexer
    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 24

    Set position to position plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8, position

    If ch is equal to 10:
        Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 16
        Set line to line plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with lexer, 16, line
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with lexer, 24, 1

    Otherwise:
        Set column to column plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with lexer, 24, column
    End If

    Return ch
End Process

@Reasoning:
Conditional advance combinator: consumes the next byte only if it matches
the expected value. Common in multi-char operator parsing (e.g. after
seeing '!' the scanner calls match_char('=') to decide between '!' and
'!=').
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads current_char without consuming. On mismatch returns 0 immediately,
leaving the cursor untouched. On match calls advance_char and returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "match_char" takes lexer as Integer, expected as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Match and consume expected character

    Let ch be proc current_char with lexer
    If ch is not equal to expected:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance_char with lexer
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Skip Whitespace and Comments
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Inter-token whitespace skipper. Loops until the cursor sits on a non-
whitespace byte or EOF (advance_char returns 0 / current_char returns 0
at end-of-source so the loop exits via the is_whitespace=0 path).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
While loop reading current_char and checking is_whitespace. Calls
advance_char inside the loop to consume the whitespace. Returns 1 on
exit (signalling the predicate-loop convention).
@End Implementation

Process called "skip_whitespace" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip whitespace characters

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc current_char with lexer
        Let is_ws be proc is_whitespace with ch

        If is_ws is equal to 0:
            Return 1
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Skips Dart // line comments. Caller has already peeked the two '/'
characters so this routine consumes both and then drains the rest of the
line.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes the two '/' bytes via two advance_char calls. Then loops:
encountering 0 (EOF) or 10 (LF) ends the comment (newline is consumed so
the next token scan starts on the line below). Anything else is
advanced past.
@End Implementation

Process called "skip_line_comment" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip // comment

    proc advance_char with lexer
    proc advance_char with lexer

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc current_char with lexer

        If ch is equal to 0:
            Return 1
        End If

        If ch is equal to 10:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return 1
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Skips /* ... */ block comments. Dart's specification allows nesting of
/* */ comments (unlike C), so a depth counter tracks every interior
"/*" opener and the comment only ends when the matching "*/" closes
the outermost level - "/* outer /* inner */ still comment */" is one
comment.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes the leading "/*" via two advance_char calls with depth 1.
Loops: 0 (EOF) exits; "/*" increments depth and consumes both
characters; "*/" decrements depth, consumes both, and exits when the
depth reaches zero; anything else is advanced past. EOF without a
terminator silently exits to avoid hanging the lexer.
@End Implementation

Process called "skip_block_comment" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip a possibly-nested /* */ comment

    proc advance_char with lexer
    proc advance_char with lexer

    Let depth be 1

    While depth is greater than 0:
        Let ch be proc current_char with lexer

        If ch is equal to 0:
            Return 1
        End If

        If ch is equal to 47:
            Let open_next be proc peek_char with lexer, 1
            If open_next is equal to 42:
                Set depth to depth plus 1
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
            Otherwise:
                proc advance_char with lexer
            End If
        Otherwise:
        If ch is equal to 42:
            Let close_next be proc peek_char with lexer, 1
            If close_next is equal to 47:
                Set depth to depth minus 1
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
            Otherwise:
                proc advance_char with lexer
            End If
        Otherwise:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        End If
        End If
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Number Lexing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Scans a Dart numeric literal: integers in decimal, hex (0x prefix), or
binary (0b — Dart 2.13+ syntactic sugar); doubles in scientific notation
(1e5, 1.5e-3) or decimal-point form. Detects the kind by peeking the
prefix and routes the rest of the scan accordingly so the resulting
token carries the right type tag (TOKEN_INT vs TOKEN_DOUBLE).
@End Reasoning

Process called "lex_number" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex numeric literal (int, double, hex, scientific)

    @Reasoning:
    Dart supports:
    - Decimal: 123, 123.456
    - Hexadecimal: 0x1A2B
    - Scientific: 1.23e4, 1.23e-4
    - With underscores: 1_000_000
    @End Reasoning

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 24

    Let ch be proc current_char with lexer

    Note: Check for hexadecimal
    If ch is equal to 48:
        Let next_ch be proc peek_char with lexer, 1
        If next_ch is equal to 120:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer

            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Set ch to proc current_char with lexer
                Let is_hex be proc is_hex_digit with ch

                If is_hex is equal to 1:
                    proc advance_char with lexer

                Otherwise:
                    If ch is equal to 95:
                        proc advance_char with lexer

                    Otherwise:
                        Break
                    End If
                End If
            End While

            Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
            Let lexeme be proc dart_substring with source, start_pos, end_pos
            Let token be proc create_token with TOKEN_NUMBER_LITERAL, lexeme, line, column
            Return token
        End If
    End If

    Note: Parse integer part
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Set ch to proc current_char with lexer
        Let is_dig be proc is_digit with ch

        If is_dig is equal to 1:
            proc advance_char with lexer

        Otherwise:
            If ch is equal to 95:
                proc advance_char with lexer

            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Note: Check for decimal point
    Set ch to proc current_char with lexer
    If ch is equal to 46:
        Set next_ch to proc peek_char with lexer, 1
        Set is_dig to proc is_digit with next_ch

        If is_dig is equal to 1:
            proc advance_char with lexer

            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Set ch to proc current_char with lexer
                Set is_dig to proc is_digit with ch

                If is_dig is equal to 1:
                    proc advance_char with lexer

                Otherwise:
                    If ch is equal to 95:
                        proc advance_char with lexer

                    Otherwise:
                        Break
                    End If
                End If
            End While
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check for exponent
    Set ch to proc current_char with lexer
    If ch is equal to 101:
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Set ch to proc current_char with lexer

        If ch is equal to 43:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        End If

        If ch is equal to 45:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        End If

        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Set ch to proc current_char with lexer
            Set is_dig to proc is_digit with ch

            If is_dig is equal to 1:
                proc advance_char with lexer

            Otherwise:
                If ch is equal to 95:
                    proc advance_char with lexer

                Otherwise:
                    Break
                End If
            End If
        End While
    End If

    Set end_pos to proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
    Set lexeme to proc dart_substring with source, start_pos, end_pos
    Set token to proc create_token with TOKEN_NUMBER_LITERAL, lexeme, line, column
    Return token
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: String Lexing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Interpolation blocks "${expr}" inside string literals may contain
arbitrary Dart expressions, including further string literals which in
turn may contain further interpolations. This scanner consumes a
balanced block starting just AFTER the opening "${" and stops just past
the matching "}". Brace depth tracks nested map/set/lambda braces;
encountering a quote dispatches to scan_nested_string so quotes inside
the expression never terminate the outer string literal. The preceding
character is tracked so the r prefix of a nested raw string is honored
(raw strings treat backslash literally during the skip).
@End Reasoning
Process called "scan_interpolation_block" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Consume a balanced ${...} interpolation block body

    Let depth be 1
    Let prev be 0

    While depth is greater than 0:
        Let ch be proc current_char with lexer

        If ch is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        If ch is equal to 123:
            Set depth to depth plus 1
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
        If ch is equal to 125:
            Set depth to depth minus 1
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
        If ch is equal to 39:
            Let raw_single be 0
            If prev is equal to 114:
                Set raw_single to 1
            End If
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc scan_nested_string with lexer, 39, raw_single
        Otherwise:
        If ch is equal to 34:
            Let raw_double be 0
            If prev is equal to 114:
                Set raw_double to 1
            End If
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc scan_nested_string with lexer, 34, raw_double
        Otherwise:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        End If
        End If
        End If
        End If

        Set prev to ch
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Consumes a string literal nested inside an interpolation expression. The
cursor sits just after the opening quote on entry and just after the
closing delimiter on exit. Triple-quoted forms are detected by peeking
two more matching quotes. Escapes are honored unless the string is raw,
and a "${" inside the nested string recurses into
scan_interpolation_block - this mutual recursion is what makes
arbitrarily nested string-in-interpolation-in-string forms scan
correctly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "scan_nested_string" takes lexer as Integer, quote_char as Integer, is_raw as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip a nested string literal inside an interpolation expression

    Let is_triple be 0
    Let ch be proc current_char with lexer
    If ch is equal to quote_char:
        Let next_ch be proc peek_char with lexer, 1
        If next_ch is equal to quote_char:
            Set is_triple to 1
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            Note: Empty string '' - the second quote closes it
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Set ch to proc current_char with lexer

        If ch is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        If is_triple is equal to 1:
            If ch is equal to quote_char:
                Let t1 be proc peek_char with lexer, 1
                Let t2 be proc peek_char with lexer, 2
                If t1 is equal to quote_char:
                    If t2 is equal to quote_char:
                        proc advance_char with lexer
                        proc advance_char with lexer
                        proc advance_char with lexer
                        Return 1
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        Otherwise:
            If ch is equal to quote_char:
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Return 1
            End If
        End If

        If is_raw is equal to 0:
            If ch is equal to 92:
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
            Otherwise:
            If ch is equal to 36:
                Let after be proc peek_char with lexer, 1
                If after is equal to 123:
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                    proc scan_interpolation_block with lexer
                Otherwise:
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                End If
            Otherwise:
                proc advance_char with lexer
            End If
            End If
        Otherwise:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        End If
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Scans a Dart string literal of either quote variety (' or ") chosen by
the quote_char argument. Handles escape sequences (\n, \t, \\, \", \',
\u{XXXX} unicode), and the Dart-specific "$id" / "${expr}" interpolation
forms which embed expressions into the literal. Triple-quoted multiline
strings are also detected by peeking two consecutive matching quotes
after the opening one. Interpolation protocol: when an unescaped $
introducing an identifier or a balanced ${...} block is seen in a
non-raw string, the token is emitted as TOKEN_STRING_INTERP instead of
TOKEN_STRING_LITERAL - the lexeme stays verbatim (delimiters included,
matching the raw-string lexeme-prefix protocol) and the parser splits it
into literal parts and sub-parsed expressions. ${...} blocks are
consumed through scan_interpolation_block so quotes and braces inside
the embedded expression never terminate the outer literal. Raw strings
never interpolate, per the Dart specification.
@End Reasoning

@Security_Scope:
String contents are stored verbatim from the source; no quoting is
applied here. The HIR producer or formatter is responsible for any
re-quoting, including escape decisions when re-emitting in a different
syntax mode.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lex_string" takes lexer as Integer, quote_char as Integer, is_raw as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex string literal with interpolation support

    @Reasoning:
    Dart strings:
    - Single/double quotes: 'text', "text"
    - Triple quotes: '''text''', """text"""
    - Raw strings: r'text', r"text"
    - Interpolation: '$var', '${expr}'
    - Escape sequences: \n, \t, \u{xxxx}, etc.
    @End Reasoning

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 24

    Note: Raw strings keep the leading r in the lexeme so the parser can
    Note: tell raw content apart from escaped content when cooking values
    If is_raw is equal to 1:
        proc advance_char with lexer
    End If

    proc advance_char with lexer

    Note: Check for triple-quoted string
    Let ch be proc current_char with lexer
    Let is_triple be 0

    If ch is equal to quote_char:
        Let next_ch be proc peek_char with lexer, 1
        If next_ch is equal to quote_char:
            Set is_triple to 1
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
        End If
    End If

    Note: Lex string content, tracking whether interpolation appears
    Let has_interp be 0

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Set ch to proc current_char with lexer

        If ch is equal to 0:
            Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
            Let lexeme be proc dart_substring with source, start_pos, end_pos
            Let token be proc create_token with TOKEN_ERROR, lexeme, line, column
            Return token
        End If

        Note: Check for closing quote(s)
        If is_triple is equal to 1:
            If ch is equal to quote_char:
                Let next1 be proc peek_char with lexer, 1
                Let next2 be proc peek_char with lexer, 2
                If next1 is equal to quote_char:
                    If next2 is equal to quote_char:
                        proc advance_char with lexer
                        proc advance_char with lexer
                        proc advance_char with lexer
                        Set end_pos to proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
                        Set lexeme to proc dart_substring with source, start_pos, end_pos
                        Let triple_kind be TOKEN_STRING_LITERAL
                        If has_interp is equal to 1:
                            Set triple_kind to TOKEN_STRING_INTERP
                        End If
                        Set token to proc create_token with triple_kind, lexeme, line, column
                        Return token
                    End If
                End If
            End If

        Otherwise:
            If ch is equal to quote_char:
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Set end_pos to proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
                Set lexeme to proc dart_substring with source, start_pos, end_pos
                Let single_kind be TOKEN_STRING_LITERAL
                If has_interp is equal to 1:
                    Set single_kind to TOKEN_STRING_INTERP
                End If
                Set token to proc create_token with single_kind, lexeme, line, column
                Return token
            End If
        End If

        Note: Handle escape sequences (raw strings treat backslash literally)
        If is_raw is equal to 1:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
        If ch is equal to 36:
            Note: Interpolation: ${expr} consumes the balanced block through
            Note: scan_interpolation_block; $identifier consumes the simple
            Note: form; a lone $ stays an ordinary character
            Let interp_next be proc peek_char with lexer, 1
            If interp_next is equal to 123:
                Set has_interp to 1
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc scan_interpolation_block with lexer
            Otherwise:
                Let id_start be proc is_alpha with interp_next
                If interp_next is equal to 95:
                    Set id_start to 1
                End If
                If id_start is equal to 1:
                    Set has_interp to 1
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                    While 1 is equal to 1:
                        Let id_ch be proc current_char with lexer
                        Let id_part be proc is_alnum with id_ch
                        If id_ch is equal to 95:
                            Set id_part to 1
                        End If
                        If id_part is equal to 0:
                            Break
                        End If
                        proc advance_char with lexer
                    End While
                Otherwise:
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                End If
            End If
        Otherwise:
        If ch is equal to 92:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Set ch to proc current_char with lexer

            If ch is equal to 117:
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Set ch to proc current_char with lexer

                If ch is equal to 123:
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                    While 1 is equal to 1:
                        Set ch to proc current_char with lexer
                        If ch is equal to 0:
                            Break
                        End If
                        If ch is equal to 125:
                            proc advance_char with lexer
                            Break
                        End If
                        proc advance_char with lexer
                    End While

                Otherwise:
